# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: reaction-mechanisms-organic
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/addition-reaction] In organic chemistry, an **addition reaction** is an organic reaction in which two or more molecules combine to form a larger molecule called the *adduct*.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/addition-reaction] An addition reaction is limited to chemical compounds that have multiple bonds.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/addition-reaction] Examples include a molecule with a carbon–carbon double bond (an alkene) or a triple bond (an alkyne).
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/addition-reaction] Another example is a compound that has rings (which are also considered points of unsaturation).
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/addition-reaction] A molecule that has carbon—heteroatom double bonds, such as a carbonyl group (C=O) or imine group (C=N), can undergo an addition reaction because its double-bond.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/addition-reaction] An addition reaction is the reverse of an elimination reaction, in which one molecule divides into two or more molecules.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/addition-reaction] For instance, the hydration of an alkene to an alcohol is reversed by dehydration.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/addition-reaction] There are two main types of polar addition reactions: electrophilic addition and nucleophilic addition.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/addition-reaction] Two non-polar addition reactions exist as well, called free-radical addition and cycloadditions.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/addition-reaction] Addition reactions are also encountered in polymerizations and called addition polymerization.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/addition-reaction] Depending on the product structure, it could promptly react further to eject a leaving group to give the addition–elimination reaction sequence.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/addition-reaction] Addition reactions are useful in analytic chemistry, as they can identify the existence and number of double bonds in a molecule.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] Until the early 1970s, carbocations were called *carbonium ions*.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] Carbonium ions, as originally defined by Olah, are characterized by a three-center two-electron delocalized bonding scheme and are essentially synonymous with so-called 'non-classical carbocations', which are carbocations that contain bridging C–C or C–H σ-bonds.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] However, others have more narrowly defined the term 'carbonium ion' as formally protonated or alkylated alkanes (CR+ 5, where R is H or alkyl), to the exclusion of non-classical carbocations like the 2-norbornyl cation.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] According to the IUPAC, a *carbocation* is any cation containing an even number of electrons in which a significant portion of the positive charge resides on a carbon atom.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] Prior to the observation of five-coordinate carbocations by Olah and coworkers, *carbocation* and *carbonium ion* were used interchangeably.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] Olah proposed a redefinition of *carbonium ion* as a carbocation featuring any type of three-center two-electron bonding, while a *carbenium ion* was newly coined to refer to a carbocation containing only two-center two-electron bonds with a three-coordinate positive carbon.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] In this usage, 2-norbornyl cation is not a carbonium ion, because it is formally derived from protonation of an alkene (norbornene) rather than an alkane, although it is a non-classical carbocation due to its bridged structure.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] The IUPAC acknowledges the three divergent definitions of carbonium ion and urges care in the usage of this term.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] For the remainder of this article, the term *carbonium ion* will be used in this latter restricted sense, while *non-classical carbocation* will be used to refer to any carbocation with C–C and/or C–H σ-bonds delocalized by bridging.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] Carbonium ions can be thought of as protonated or alkylated alkanes, bearing the general formula CR5+ (R = alkyl or H).
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] A typical example is the methanium ion, CH5+, which is formed by protonation of methane using a superacid.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] By necessity of having five bonds on carbon but only four valence electron pairs available for bonding, they feature delocalized 3c-2e σ bonding and are thus regarded as type of non-classical carbocation.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] Like carbenium ions, carbonium ions are often invoked as intermediates in the upgrading of hydrocarbons in refineries.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] They are generally fleeting intermediates with fluxional structures that are challenging to observe and interpret spectroscopically.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] They can undergo decomposition by expulsion of a proton or alkyl group, or by loss of H2 to give a carbenium ion.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] At least in a formal sense, carbenium ions (CR3+) are derived from the protonation (addition of H+) or alkylation (addition of R+) of a carbene or alkene.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] They admit a resonance depiction in which one carbon atom bears a formal positive charge and is surrounded by six valence electrons instead of the usual octet.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] Therefore, carbenium ions (and carbocations in general) are often reactive, seeking to fill the valence octet and regain a neutral charge.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] In accord with VSEPR and Bent's rule, unless geometrically constrained to be pyramidal (e.g., 1-adamantyl cation), 3-coordinate carbon in carbenium ions are usually trigonal planar and *sp*2 hybridized; the lowest unoccupied molecular orbital is an empty pure *p* orbital pointing out-of-plane.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] A prototypical example is the *t-*butyl cation, CMe+3.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] There is, in fact, an entire spectrum of bonding scenarios between a slight lean due to hyperconjugation to a fully symmetric bridging structure featuring 3c2e bonding.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] Consequently, there is no firm dividing line between "classical" and the so-called "non-classical" structures.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] Non-classical carbenium ions feature also σ delocalization (3c2e bonds) in their bonding but have the general formula CR3+ (R = alkyl or H).
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] Thus, in principle, one can propose non-bridged, classical structures for these cations, as well as a bridged non-classical structure.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] Because of the subtle differences in the expected behavior of a non-classical carbenium ions compared to the alternative hypothesis of two rapidly equilibrating classical structures, a lively and often acrimonious debate took place over several decades regarding the merits of each model.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] For a detailed history of this dispute, see the article on the 2-norbornyl cation.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] Currently, there is overwhelming evidence that, at least in some cases (notably the extremely well-studied 2-norbornyl cation), the equilibrium structure of a carbenium ion is non-classical, although even minor changes in structure could result in a classical structure being favored.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] The history of carbocations dates back to 1891 when G.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] Merling reported that he added bromine to tropylidene (cycloheptatriene) and then heated the product to obtain a crystalline, water-soluble material, C 7H 7Br.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] He did not suggest a structure for it; however, Doering and Knox convincingly showed that it was tropylium (cycloheptatrienylium) bromide.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] This ion is predicted to be aromatic by Hückel's rule.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] In 1902, Norris and Kehrman independently discovered that colorless triphenylmethanol gives deep-yellow solutions in concentrated sulfuric acid.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] Triphenylmethyl chloride similarly formed orange complexes when treated with aluminium and tin chlorides.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] In 1902, Adolf von Baeyer recognized the salt-like character of the compounds formed.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] He dubbed the relationship between color and salt formation **halochromy**, of which malachite green is a prime example.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] The trityl carbocation (shown below) is indeed a stable carbocationic system, for example in the form of trityl hexafluorophosphate.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] Carbocations are reactive intermediates in many organic reactions.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] This idea, first proposed by Julius Stieglitz in 1899, was further developed by Hans Meerwein in his 1922 study of the Wagner–Meerwein rearrangement.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] Carbocations were also found to be involved in the SN1 reaction, the E1 reaction, and in rearrangement reactions such as the Whitmore 1,2 shift.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] The chemical establishment was reluctant to accept the notion of a carbocation and for a long time the Journal of the American Chemical Society refused articles that mentioned them.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] An NMR spectrum of a carbocation was first reported by Doering et al. in 1958.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] It was the heptamethylbenzenium ion, made by treating hexamethylbenzene with methyl chloride and aluminium chloride.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] The stable 7-norbornadienyl cation was prepared by Story et al. in 1960 by reacting norbornadienyl chloride with silver tetrafluoroborate in sulfur dioxide at −80 °C.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] The NMR spectrum established that it was non-classically bridged (the first stable non-classical ion observed).
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] In 1962, Olah directly observed the *tert*-butyl carbocation by nuclear magnetic resonance as a stable species on dissolving *tert*-butyl fluoride in magic acid.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] The NMR spectrum of the norbornyl cation was reported by Schleyer et al.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/carbocation] It was shown to rapidly undergo proton-scrambling.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] The most widely practised example of this reaction is the ethylation of benzene.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] (After dehydrogenation and polymerization, the commodity plastic polystyrene is produced.) In this process, acids are used as catalyst to generate the incipient carbocation.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] Many other electrophilic reactions of benzene are conducted, although on a much smaller scale; they are valuable routes to key intermediates.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] The nitration of benzene is achieved via the action of the nitronium ion as the electrophile.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] The sulfonation with fuming sulfuric acid gives benzenesulfonic acid.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] Aromatic halogenation with bromine, chlorine, or iodine gives the corresponding aryl halides, this reaction is typically catalyzed by the corresponding iron or aluminum trihalide.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] The Friedel–Crafts reaction can be performed either as an acylation or as an alkylation.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] Often, aluminium trichloride is used, but almost any strong Lewis acid can be applied.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] For the acylation reaction a stoichiometric amount of aluminum trichloride is required.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] The overall reaction mechanism, denoted by the Hughes–Ingold mechanistic symbol **SEAr**, begins with the aromatic ring attacking the electrophile E+ (1).
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] This step leads to the formation of a positively charged and delocalized cyclohexadienyl cation, also known as an arenium ion, Wheland intermediate, or arene σ-complex (2).
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] Many examples of this carbocation have been characterized, but under normal operating conditions these highly acidic species will donate the proton attached to the sp3 carbon to the solvent (or any other weak base) to reestablish aromaticity.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] The net result is the replacement of H by E in the aryl ring (3).
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] The capacity of these types of substituents to leave is sometimes exploited synthetically, particularly the case of replacement of silyl by another functional group (*ipso* attack).
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] However, the loss of groups like iodo or alkyl is more often an undesired side reaction.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] Both the regioselectivity—the diverse arene substitution patterns—and the speed of an electrophilic aromatic substitution are affected by the substituents already attached to the benzene ring.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] In terms of regioselectivity, some groups promote substitution at the ortho or para positions, whereas other groups favor substitution at the meta position.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] These groups are called either **ortho–para directing** or **meta directing**, respectively.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] In addition, some groups will increase the rate of reaction (**activating**) while others will decrease the rate (**deactivating**).
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] While the patterns of regioselectivity can be explained with resonance structures, the influence on kinetics can be explained by both resonance structures and the inductive effect.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] Substituents can generally be divided into two classes regarding electrophilic substitution: activating and deactivating towards the aromatic ring.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] **Activating substituents** or activating groups stabilize the cationic intermediate formed during the substitution by donating electrons into the ring system, by either inductive effect or resonance effects.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] Examples of activated aromatic rings are toluene, aniline and phenol.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] The extra electron density delivered into the ring by the substituent is not distributed evenly over the entire ring but is concentrated on atoms 2, 4 and 6, so activating substituents are also ortho/para directors (see below).
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] On the other hand, **deactivating substituents** destabilize the intermediate cation and thus decrease the reaction rate by either inductive or resonance effects.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] They do so by withdrawing electron density from the aromatic ring.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] The deactivation of the aromatic system means that generally harsher conditions are required to drive the reaction to completion.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] An example of this is the nitration of toluene during the production of trinitrotoluene (TNT).
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] Groups that are electron-withdrawing by resonance decrease the electron density especially at positions 2, 4 and 6, leaving positions 3 and 5 as the ones with comparably higher reactivity, so these types of groups are meta directors (see below).
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] Halogens are electronegative, so they are deactivating by induction, but they have lone pairs, so they are resonance donors and therefore ortho/para directors.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] Groups with unshared pairs of electrons, such as the amino group of aniline, are strongly *activating* (sometimes deactivating also in case of halides) and *ortho/para*-directing by resonance.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] Such activating groups donate those unshared electrons to the *pi* system, creating a negative charge on the ortho and para positions.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] These positions are thus the most reactive towards an electron-poor electrophile.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] This increased reactivity might be offset by steric hindrance between activating group and electrophile but on the other hand there are two ortho positions for reaction but only one para position.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] Hence the final outcome of the electrophilic aromatic substitution is difficult to predict, and it is usually only established by doing the reaction and observing the ratio of ortho versus para substitution.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] This substantially enhances the stability of the cationic intermediate.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] When the electrophile attacks the meta position, the nitrogen atom cannot donate electron density to the *pi* system, giving only three resonance contributors.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] This reasoning is consistent with low yields of meta-substituted product.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] Other substituents, such as the alkyl and aryl substituents, may also donate electron density to the *pi* system; however, since they lack an available unshared pair of electrons, their ability to do this is rather limited.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] Thus, they only weakly activate the ring and do not strongly disfavor the *meta* position.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] Directed ortho metalation is a special type of EAS with special **ortho directors**.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] Non-halogen groups with atoms that are more electronegative than carbon, such as a carboxylic acid group (-CO2H), withdraw substantial electron density from the *pi* system.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] These groups are strongly deactivating groups.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] Additionally, since the substituted carbon is already electron-poor, any structure having a resonance contributor in which there is a positive charge on the carbon bearing the electron-withdrawing group (i.e., *ortho* or *para* attack) is less stable than the others.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] Therefore, these electron-withdrawing groups are *meta* directing because this is the position that does not have as much destabilization.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] The reaction is also much slower (a relative reaction rate of 6×10−8 compared to benzene) because the ring is less nucleophilic.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] Although discussions of directing groups usually focus on electronic effects (e.g.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] EWG vs EDGs), steric effect can prove influential.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] Thus, nitration of toluene gives approximately 2:1 ortho vs para-nitrotoluene.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] In the case of tert-butylbenzene, however, the selectivity is reversed: 73% of the product is 4-nitro-tert-butybenzene.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] Compared to benzene, the rate of electrophilic substitution on pyridine is much slower, due to the higher electronegativity of the nitrogen atom.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] Additionally, the nitrogen in pyridine easily gets a positive charge either by protonation (from nitration or sulfonation) or Lewis acids (such as AlCl3) used to catalyze the reaction.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] This makes the reaction even slower by having adjacent formal charges on carbon and nitrogen or 2 formal charges on a localised atom.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] Doing an electrophilic substitution directly in pyridine is nearly impossible.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] In order to do the reaction, they can be made by 2 possible reactions, which are both indirect.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] One possible way to do a substitution on pyridine is nucleophilic aromatic substitution.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] Even with no catalysts, the nitrogen atom, being electronegative, can hold the negative charge by itself.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] Another way is to do an oxidation before the electrophilic substitution.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] This makes pyridine *N*-oxide, which due to the negative oxygen atom, makes the reaction faster than pyridine, and even benzene.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] The oxide then can be reduced to the substituted pyridine.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] The attachment of an entering group to a position in an aromatic compound already carrying a substituent group (other than hydrogen).
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] The entering group may displace that substituent group but may also itself be expelled or migrate to another position in a subsequent step.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] The term '*ipso*-substitution' is not used, since it is synonymous with substitution.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] A classic example is the reaction of salicylic acid with a mixture of nitric and sulfuric acid to form picric acid.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] The nitration of the 2 position involves the loss of CO2 as the leaving group.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] Desulfonation in which a sulfonyl group is substituted by a proton is a common example.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] In aromatics substituted by silicon, the silicon reacts by *ipso* substitution.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] Compared to benzene, furans, thiophenes, and pyrroles are more susceptible to electrophilic attack.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] These compounds all contain an atom with an unshared pair of electrons (oxygen, sulfur, or nitrogen) as a member of the aromatic ring, which substantially stabilizes the cationic intermediate.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] Examples of electrophilic substitutions to pyrrole are the Pictet–Spengler reaction and the Bischler–Napieralski reaction.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] Electrophilic aromatic substitutions with prochiral carbon electrophiles have been adapted for asymmetric synthesis by switching to chiral Lewis acid catalysts especially in Friedel–Crafts type reactions.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] An early example concerns the addition of chloral to phenols catalyzed by aluminium chloride modified with (–)-menthol.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/electrophilic-aromatic-substitution] In the presence of 10–20 % chiral catalyst, 80–90% ee is achievable.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] An **elimination reaction** is a type of organic reaction in which two substituents are removed from a molecule in either a one- or two-step reaction mechanism.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] The most common types of reaction mechanisms are a one-step mechanism known as the **E2 reaction** and a two-step mechanism is known as the **E1 reaction**.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] The numbers in the Hughes–Ingold symbols refer not to the number of steps in the mechanism, but rather to the molecularity of the reaction kinetics: E2 is bimolecular (second-order) while E1 is [nimolecular (first-order).
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] In cases where the molecule is able to stabilize an anion but possesses a poor leaving group, a third type of reaction, E1CB, exists.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] Finally, the pyrolysis of xanthate and acetate esters proceed through an "internal" elimination mechanism, the Ei mechanism.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] All of these reactions involve loss of sigma bonded groups to form a pi bond on the structure, such as loss of hydrogen and halogen atoms from an alkane to form an alkene.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] The E2 mechanism is a **bimolecular elimination**.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] An example of this type of reaction in *scheme 1* is the reaction of isobutylbromide with potassium ethoxide in ethanol.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] The reaction products are isobutene, ethanol and potassium bromide.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] The E1 mechanism is a **unimolecular elimination**.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] results from antiperiplanar elimination.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] is an indication that an E1 mechanism is occurring.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] An example in *scheme 2* is the reaction of tert-butylbromide with potassium ethoxide in ethanol.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] E1 eliminations happen with highly substituted alkyl halides for two main reasons.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] If SN1 and E1 pathways are competing, the E1 pathway can be favored by increasing the heat.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] Elimination is uncommon in radical-mediated reactions, but radicals can eliminate stabilized moieties to give olefins.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] Here, the new radical is generated on the polymer chain, which can further undergo a similar type of reaction to generate more styrene molecules.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] Here a radical abstracts a hydrogen atom from another same radical to form two non-radical species: an alkane and an alkene.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] Radical elimination reactions are found in enzyme-catalyzed pathways.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] In the dehydrogenation reaction of acyl-CoA to form enoyl-CoA, FAD accepts two protons and two electrons to form FADH2 under the catalysis of acyl-CoA dehydrogenase.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] The reaction rate is influenced by the reactivity of halogens, iodide and bromide being favored.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] Fluoride is not a good leaving group, so eliminations with fluoride as the leaving group have slower rates than other halogens .
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] There is a certain level of competition between the elimination reaction and nucleophilic substitution.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] More precisely, there are competitions between E2 and SN2 and also between E1 and SN1.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] For example, when a 3° haloalkane is reacts with an alkoxide, due to strong basic character of the alkoxide and unreactivity of 3° group towards SN2, only alkene formation by E2 elimination is observed.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] Thus, elimination by E2 limits the scope of the Williamson ether synthesis (an SN2 reaction) to essentially only 1° haloalkanes; 2° haloalkanes generally do not give synthetically useful yields, while 3° haloalkanes fail completely.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] With strong base, 3° haloalkanes give elimination by E2.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] With weak bases, mixtures of elimination and substitution products form by competing SN1 and E1 pathways.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] The case of 2° haloalkanes is relatively complex.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] For strongly basic nucleophiles (p*K*aH > 11, e.g., hydroxide, alkoxide, acetylide), the result is generally elimination by E2, while weaker bases that are still good nucleophiles (e.g., acetate, azide, cyanide, iodide) will give primarily SN2.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] Finally, weakly nucleophilic species (e.g., water, alcohols, carboxylic acids) will give a mixture of SN1 and E1.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] For 1° haloalkanes with β-branching, E2 elimination is still generally preferred over SN2 for strongly basic nucleophiles.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] Unhindered 1° haloalkanes favor SN2 when the nucleophile is also unhindered.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] However, strongly basic and hindered nucleophiles favor E2.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] On the other hand, clean E2 can be achieved by simply selecting a sterically hindered base (e.g., potassium *tert*-butoxide).
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] Similarly, attempts to effect substitution by SN1 almost always result in a product mixture contaminated by some E1 product (again, with the exception of cases where the lack of β hydrogens makes elimination impossible).
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] In one study the kinetic isotope effect (KIE) was determined for the gas phase reaction of several alkyl halides with the chlorate ion.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] In accordance with an E2 elimination the reaction with t-butyl chloride results in a KIE of 2.3.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] The methyl chloride reaction (only SN2 possible) on the other hand has a KIE of 0.85 consistent with a SN2 reaction because in this reaction type the C-H bonds tighten in the transition state.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] The KIE's for the ethyl (0.99) and isopropyl (1.72) analogues suggest competition between the two reaction modes.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] β-Elimination, with loss of electrofuge and nucleofuge on vicinal carbon atoms, is by far the most common type of elimination.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] The ability to form a stable product containing a C=C or C=X bond, as well as orbital alignment considerations, strongly favors β-elimination over other elimination processes.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] However, other types are known, generally for systems where β-elimination cannot occur.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] The next most common type of elimination reaction is α-elimination.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] For a carbon center, the result of α-elimination is the formation of a carbene, which includes "stable carbenes" such as carbon monoxide or isocyanides.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] For instance, α-elimination the elements of HCl from chloroform (CHCl3) in the presence of strong base is a classic approach for the generation of dichlorocarbene, :CCl2, as a reactive intermediate.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] (Confusingly, in organometallic terminology, the terms *α-elimination* and *α-abstraction* refer to processes that result in formation of a metal-carbene complex.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] In certain special cases, γ- and higher eliminations to form three-membered or larger rings is also possible in both organic and organometallic processes.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] For instance, certain Pt(II) complexes undergo γ- and δ-elimination to give metallocycles.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] More recently, γ-silyl elimination of a silylcyclobutyl tosylate has been used to prepare strained bicyclic systems.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/elimination-reaction] Many of the concepts and terminology related to elimination reactions were proposed by Christopher Kelk Ingold in the 1920s.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] In organic chemistry, **Markovnikov's rule** or **Markownikoff's rule** describes the outcome of some addition reactions.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] The rule was formulated by Russian chemist Vladimir Markovnikov in 1870.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] This is in contrast to Markovnikov's original definition, in which the rule states that the X component is added to the carbon with the fewest hydrogen atoms while the hydrogen atom is added to the carbon with the greatest number of hydrogen atoms.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] The same is true when an alkene reacts with water in an addition reaction to form an alcohol that involves carbocation formation.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] The hydroxyl group (OH) bonds to the carbon that has the greater number of carbon-carbon bonds, while the hydrogen bonds to the carbon on the other end of the double bond, that has more carbon–hydrogen bonds.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] The chemical basis for Markovnikov's Rule is the formation of the most stable carbocation during the addition process.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] Adding the hydrogen ion to one carbon atom in the alkene creates a positive charge on the other carbon, forming a carbocation intermediate.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] The more substituted the carbocation, the more stable it is, due to induction and hyperconjugation.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] The major product of the addition reaction will be the one formed from the more stable intermediate.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] Therefore, the major product of the addition of HX (where X is some atom more electronegative than H) to an alkene has the hydrogen atom in the less substituted position and X in the more substituted position.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] But the other less substituted, less stable carbocation will still be formed at some concentration and will proceed to be the minor product with the opposite, conjugate attachment of X.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] Also called **Kharasch effect** (named after Morris S.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] Kharasch), these reactions that do not involve a carbocation intermediate may react through other mechanisms that have regioselectivities not dictated by Markovnikov's rule, such as free radical addition.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] Such reactions are said to be **anti-Markovnikov**, since the halogen adds to the less substituted carbon, the opposite of a Markovnikov reaction.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] The anti-Markovnikov rule can be illustrated using the addition of hydrogen bromide to isobutylene in the presence of benzoyl peroxide or hydrogen peroxide.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] The reaction of HBr with substituted alkenes was prototypical in the study of free-radical additions.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] Early chemists discovered that the reason for the variability in the ratio of Markovnikov to anti-Markovnikov reaction products was due to the unexpected presence of free radical ionizing substances such as peroxides.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] The explanation is that the O-O bond in peroxides is relatively weak.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] With the aid of light, heat, or sometimes even just acting on its own, the O-O bond can split to form 2 radicals.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] The radical groups can then interact with HBr to produce a Br radical, which then reacts with the double bond.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] Since the bromine atom is relatively large, it is more likely to encounter and react with the least substituted carbon since this interaction produces less static interactions between the carbon and the bromine radical.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] Furthermore, similar to a positive charged species, the radical species is most stable when the unpaired electron is in the more substituted position.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] The radical intermediate is stabilized by hyperconjugation.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] In the more substituted position, more carbon-hydrogen bonds are aligned with the radical's electron deficient molecular orbital.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] This means that there are greater hyperconjugation effects, so that position is more favorable.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] In this case, the terminal carbon is a reactant that produces a primary addition product instead of a secondary addition product.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] A new method of anti-Markovnikov addition has been described by Hamilton and Nicewicz, who utilize aromatic molecules and light energy from a low-energy diode to turn the alkene into a cation radical.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] Anti-Markovnikov behaviour extends to more chemical reactions than additions to alkenes.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] Anti-Markovnikov behavior can also manifest itself in certain rearrangement reactions.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] This product distribution can be rationalized by assuming that loss of the hydroxy group in **1** gives the tertiary carbocation **A**, which rearranges to the seemingly less stable secondary carbocation **B**.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] Chlorine can approach this center from two faces leading to the observed mixture of isomers.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/markovnikov-s-rule] Another notable example of anti-Markovnikov addition is hydroboration.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] In organic chemistry, a **pericyclic reaction** is the type of organic reaction wherein the transition state of the molecule has a cyclic geometry, the reaction progresses in a concerted fashion, and the bond orbitals involved in the reaction overlap in a continuous cycle at the transition state.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] Pericyclic reactions stand in contrast to *linear reactions*, encompassing most organic transformations and proceeding through an acyclic transition state, on the one hand and *coarctate reactions*, which proceed through a doubly cyclic, concerted transition state on the other hand.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] Pericyclic reactions are usually rearrangement or addition reactions.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] The major classes of pericyclic reactions are given in the table below (the three most important classes are shown in bold).
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] Ene reactions and cheletropic reactions are often classed as group transfer reactions and cycloadditions/cycloeliminations, respectively, while dyotropic reactions and group transfer reactions (if ene reactions are excluded) are rarely encountered.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] In general, these are considered to be equilibrium processes, although it is possible to push the reaction in one direction by designing a reaction by which the product is at a significantly lower energy level; this is due to a unimolecular interpretation of Le Chatelier's principle.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] There is thus a set of "retro" pericyclic reactions.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] By definition, pericyclic reactions proceed through a concerted mechanism involving a single, cyclic transition state.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] Because of this, prior to a systematic understanding of pericyclic processes through the *principle of orbital symmetry conservation*, they were facetiously referred to as 'no-mechanism reactions'.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] However, reactions for which pericyclic mechanisms can be drawn often have related stepwise mechanisms proceeding through radical or dipolar intermediates that are also viable.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] Some classes of pericyclic reactions, such as the [2+2] ketene cycloaddition reactions, can be 'controversial' because their mechanism is sometimes not definitively known to be concerted (or may depend on the reactive system).
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] Moreover, pericyclic reactions also often have metal-catalyzed analogs, although usually these are also not technically pericyclic, since they proceed via metal-stabilized intermediates, and therefore are not concerted.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] Despite these caveats, the theoretical understanding of pericyclic reactions is probably among the most sophisticated and well-developed in all of organic chemistry.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] The understanding of how orbitals interact in the course of a pericyclic process has led to the **Woodward–Hoffmann rules**, a simple set of criteria to predict whether a pericyclic mechanism for a reaction is likely or favorable.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] For instance, these rules predict that the [4+2] cycloaddition of butadiene and ethylene under thermal conditions is likely a pericyclic process, while the [2+2] cycloaddition of two ethylene molecules is not.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] These are consistent with experimental data, supporting an ordered, concerted transition state for the former and a multistep radical process for the latter.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] Several equivalent approaches, outlined below, lead to the same predictions.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] The **aromatic transition state theory** assumes that the minimum energy transition state for a pericyclic process is aromatic, with the choice of reaction topology determined by the number of electrons involved.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] In 4*n*-electron systems (4, 8, 12, ... electrons; even number of electron pairs) Möbius topology transition states are proposed, in which the reacting molecules have orbitals interacting in a *twisted* continuous cycle with an odd number of nodes.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] The corresponding (4*n* + 2)-electron Möbius and 4*n*-electron Hückel transition states are antiaromatic and are thus strongly disfavored.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] Reactions are favorable ('allowed') if the ground state of the reactants correlate with the ground state of the products, while they are unfavorable ('forbidden') if the ground state of the reactants correlate with an excited state of the products.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] This idea is known as the *conservation of orbital symmetry*.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] Consideration of the interactions of the highest occupied and lowest unoccupied molecular orbitals (**frontier orbital analysis**) is another approach to analyzing the transition state of a pericyclic reaction.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] The arrow-pushing convention for pericyclic reactions has a somewhat different meaning compared to polar (and radical) reactions.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] For pericyclic reactions, there is often no obvious movement of electrons from an electron rich source to an electron poor sink.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] Rather, electrons are redistributed around a cyclic transition state.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] Thus, electrons can be pushed in either of two directions for a pericyclic reaction.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] For some pericyclic reactions, however, there is a definite polarization of charge at the transition state due to asynchronicity (bond formation and breaking do not occur to a uniform extent at the transition state).
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] Thus, one direction may be preferred over another, although arguably, both depictions are still formally correct.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] In the case of the Diels-Alder reaction shown below, resonance arguments make clear the direction of polarization.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] In more complex situations, however, detailed computations may be needed to determine the direction and extent of polarization.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] Closely related to pericyclic processes are reactions that are **pseudopericyclic**.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] Although a *pseudopericyclic reaction* proceeds through a cyclic transition state, two of the orbitals involved are constrained to be orthogonal and cannot interact.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] Perhaps the most famous example is the hydroboration of an olefin.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] Although this appears to be a 4-electron Hückel topology forbidden group transfer process, the empty p orbital and sp2 hybridized B–H bond are orthogonal and do not interact.
[src:reaction-mechanisms-organic/pericyclic-reaction] Hence, the Woodward-Hoffmann rules do not apply.
